# Figma-to-Code Rule

When given a Figma frame, first translate it into an implementation specification before coding.

## Before coding, identify

1. Screen purpose
2. Layout regions
3. Visual hierarchy
4. Reusable existing components
5. New components needed
6. Primary interactions
7. Secondary interactions
8. Required data
9. Local state
10. Server/API state assumptions
11. Empty, loading, error, and success states
12. Responsive behavior
13. Accessibility requirements
14. Risks or ambiguities

## Design translation principles

- Preserve hierarchy and spacing relationships.
- Convert repeated styles into reusable tokens or classes.
- Use semantic layout instead of absolute positioning when possible.
- Avoid blindly copying every pixel value.
- Prefer scalable components over one-off Figma replicas.
- Preserve product intent over superficial pixel matching.
- Map screens to `src/app/pages/`; update `.component.ts` / `.component.html`.

## Guardrails

- Do not hardcode text and data deep inside reusable components.
- Do not create a new button, input, modal, or card style if one already exists.
- Do not ignore responsive behavior just because the Figma frame is desktop-sized.
- Do not assume a static mockup represents every app state.
